# MCP-first Memory Rules

This is secondary legacy Cursor compatibility guidance. For VS Code/Copilot sessions, prefer `.github/copilot-instructions.md` and `.github/instructions/pegasus-memory.instructions.md`.

Use `pegasus-memory-mcp` as the operational memory interface for recovery, search, and writes. This legacy Cursor guidance must not contradict the Copilot-first MCP memory policy.

At session start or after context compaction:

1. Recover active project/change context through MCP when available.
2. Search MCP memory for decisions, constraints, task progress, handoffs, observations, and learnings.
3. Read `docs/pegasus/prd.md`, `docs/pegasus/proposal.md`, `docs/pegasus/spec.md`, `docs/pegasus/design.md`, `docs/pegasus/tasks.md`, and `docs/pegasus/apply-progress.md` for file-based SDD artifacts.
4. Avoid duplicate launches by comparing MCP task progress with `docs/pegasus/apply-progress.md`.

When work changes facts, decisions, task status, blockers, artifacts, handoffs, or gotchas, save the durable record through MCP when available and merge implementation status into `docs/pegasus/apply-progress.md` when relevant.

If `pegasus-memory-mcp` is unavailable, show exactly: `El pegasus-memory-mcp no se encuentra disponible, si continuamos con eso asi, no se guardara nada de lo que hagamos en memoria persistente`. Project/change artifact work may continue, but do not claim persistent memory was saved and do not fall back to Markdown memory.

Do not write retrospective Markdown memory. `docs/pegasus/memory/` is deprecated and is not an active backend, fallback, or co-source for operational memory.
